{"id":"1402.3308","submitter":"Rebecca Martin","authors":"Rebecca G. Martin, Mario Livio","title":"On the evolution of the CO snow line in protoplanetary disks","comments":"Accepted for publication in ApJ Letters","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/2041-8205/783/2/L28","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  CO is thought to be a vital building block for prebiotic molecules that are\nnecessary for life. Thus, understanding where CO existed in a solid phase\nwithin the solar nebula is important for understanding the origin of life. We\nmodel the evolution of the CO snow line in a protoplanetary disk. We find that\nthe current observed location of the CO snow line in our solar system, and in\nthe solar system analogue TW Hydra, cannot be explained by a fully turbulent\ndisk model. With time-dependent disk models we find that the inclusion of a\ndead zone (a region of low turbulence) can resolve this problem. Furthermore,\nwe obtain a fully analytic solution for the CO snow line radius for late disk\nevolutionary times. This will be useful for future observational attempts to\ncharacterize the demographics and predict the composition and habitability of\nexoplanets.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Feb 2014 21:30:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-03-05"}
